paragraphs.title: Zeppelin Demo Notebook 2
paragraphs.text:
%md
Demonstrate loading, querying, visualizing, and saving the GroupLens MovieLens Latest Datasets.
The latest datasets are available to download on [GroupLens](https://grouplens.org/datasets/movielens/).

MovieLens Datasets Specifications:
- Small: __100,000__ ratings and 3,600 tag applications applied to 9,000 movies by 600 users. Last updated 9/2018.
- Full: __27,000,000__ ratings and 1,100,000 tag applications applied to 58,000 movies by 280,000 users. Includes tag genome data with 14 million relevance scores across 1,100 tags. Last updated 9/2018.

paragraphs.title: Load MovieLens Data from GroupLens
paragraphs.text:
%sh
#change me - choices: or ml-latest-small (100k) or ml-latest (27MM)
DIR="ml-latest-small"

if [ -d $DIR ]; then
    echo "$DIR exist"
else 
    wget -nv http://files.grouplens.org/datasets/movielens/$DIR.zip -O $DIR.zip && unzip $DIR.zip
fi

# copy from local file system (/var/lib/zeppelin) to the destination file system (/user/zeppelin)
hadoop fs -put -f  $DIR/movies.csv $DIR/ratings.csv .
hadoop fs -ls -h .

paragraphs.title: Download DDL from S3 and Execute Against RDS
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
import boto3
import psycopg2
import csv

s3 = boto3.client('s3')
s3.download_file(ZEPPELIN_DEMO_BUCKET, "bootstrap/ratings.sql", "ratings.sql")

conn = psycopg2.connect(RDS_CONN_STR)
conn.autocommit = True
cursor = conn.cursor()

sql_file = open("ratings.sql", "r")
sqlFile = sql_file.read()
sql_file.close()
sqlCommands = sqlFile.split(";")
for command in sqlCommands:
    print(command)
    if command.strip() != "":
        cursor.execute(command)

-- Create simple 'Movie Ratings' PostgreSQL database schema (DDL)

COMMENT ON SCHEMA public IS 'standard public schema'


ALTER SCHEMA public OWNER TO masteruser


CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS movies (
    movieId bigint NOT NULL CONSTRAINT movies_pkey PRIMARY KEY,
    title text NOT NULL,
    genres text NOT NULL
)


ALTER TABLE movies OWNER TO masteruser


CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS ratings (
    userId bigint NOT NULL,
    movieId bigint NOT NULL CONSTRAINT ratings_movies_movie_id_fk REFERENCES movies ON UPDATE RESTRICT ON DELETE RESTRICT,
    rating numeric (2, 1) NOT NULL,
    timestamp bigint NOT NULL
)

paragraphs.title: Import Movies from CSV File to RDS
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
# source: https://www.dataquest.io/blog/loading-data-into-postgres/
# the slow way since the titles contain commas
with open("ml-latest-small/movies.csv", "r") as f:
    reader = csv.reader(f)
    next(reader)  # Skip the header row.
    for row in reader:
        cursor.execute(
            "INSERT INTO movies (movieId, title, genres) VALUES (%s, %s, %s)",
            row
        )
        conn.commit()

paragraphs.title: Import Ratings from CSV File to RDS
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
# the fast way...
with open("ml-latest-small/ratings.csv", "r") as f:
    # Notice that we don"t need the `csv` module.
    next(f) # Skip the header row.
    cursor.copy_from(f, "ratings", sep=",", columns=("userId", "movieId", "rating", "timestamp"))
    conn.commit()

paragraphs.title: Create Temporary View of Ratings Data and Query
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark

ratingsDF.createOrReplaceTempView("ratings")

ratingsDF = spark.sql("SELECT movieId, rating, userId, CAST(timestamp as timestamp) as dateTime " +
                      "FROM ratings " +
                      "ORDER BY movieId, rating, userId")

print("DataFrame rows: %d" % ratingsDF.count())
ratingsDF.show(10, False)

paragraphs.title: Replace Temporary View with New Query
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
ratingsDF.createOrReplaceTempView("ratings")
moviesDF.createOrReplaceTempView("movies")

topMoviesDF = spark.sql("SELECT m.title, AVG(r.rating) as avg_rating, COUNT(r.rating) as cnt_ratings " +
                        "FROM ratings r " +
                        "JOIN movies m ON (r.movieId = m.movieId) " +
                        "GROUP BY m.title " +
                        "ORDER BY avg_rating DESC, cnt_ratings DESC, m.title ASC")
                        
# topMoviesDF = topMoviesDF.filter(topMoviesDF.cnt_ratings >= 25)

print("DataFrame rows: %d" % moviesDF.count())
print("Top 10 Movies")
topMoviesDF.show(10, False)

paragraphs.title: Native Zeppelin Visualization Based on SQL Query
paragraphs.text:
%sql
WITH tmp_table AS (
    SELECT m.title, AVG(r.rating) as avg_rating, COUNT(r.rating) as cnt_ratings
    FROM ratings r
    JOIN movies m ON (r.movieId = m.movieId)
    GROUP BY m.title)
    
SELECT title, CAST(avg_rating AS DECIMAL(38,2)), cnt_ratings
FROM tmp_table
WHERE avg_rating >= ${avgRatingMin=4} AND cnt_ratings >= ${RatingsMin=2}
ORDER BY avg_rating ASC, cnt_ratings DESC, title ASC
LIMIT 25
